==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expletive
<hw>Ex"ple*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>expletivus</ets>, from <ets>expletus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>explere</ets> to fill up; <ets>ex</ets> out+<ets>plere</ets> to
fill, akin to <ets>plenus</ets> full: cf. F. <ets>expl⟦eacute⟧tif</ets>.
See <er>Full</er>.]</ety> <def>Filling up; hence, added merely for the
purpose of filling up; superfluous.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Expletive</xex>
imagery.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hallam.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Expletive</qex> phrases to plump his speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expletive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Expletive
<hw>Ex"ple*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A word, letter, or syllable not
necessary to the sense, but inserted to fill a vacancy; an
oath.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While <qex>explectives</qex> their feeble aid to join,⟦br⟧
And ten low words oft creep in one dull line.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expletively</ent>⟦br⟧
